Zcash privacy is consensus-level; Railgun privacy is application-level (a contract anyone can audit and interact with directly on-chain)

While the counterfeit ZEC issue last week doesn’t transfer to RAIL it’s worth noting there are are separate “possible” vulnerabilities: 

1) Railgun’s SNARK requires a trusted setup that generates toxic waste. If the secret parameters were ever retained by a participant (or the ceremony was compromised), an attacker could forge proofs and mint shielded value out of nothing, undetectably

2) Smart contract bugs: Because Railgun lives in Solidity on Ethereum, it also inherits the entire EVM contract attack surface: upgrade logic, access control, the wrap/unwrap boundary where ERC-20s enter and leave the shielded pool. That boundary is the highest-value target because it’s where real tokens actually move

Other risks:

- related / meta data leakage: privacy can degrade through contract timing 

- compliance/reg: see tornado cash friction points 

